The above results suggested that numerous oxygen-containing functional groups of GH-CDs could achieve ROS/RNS scavenging by adsorption of free radicals to form adducts and their depletion by electron transfer. Building on the promising ROS/RNS scavenging outcomes observed with GH-CDs, we investigated the antioxidant and anti-inflammatory impacts of GH-CDs on RAW 264.7 cells. Uptake of drugs in cells is a prerequisite for their function, and thus the cellular uptake of GH-CDs was investigated before the next experiments. As shown in the flow cytometry and fluorescence imaging results, the cellular uptake of the GH-CDs gradually increased over time (
                           Figure S4
                        ). To further investigate the ROS-scavenging efficacy of GH-CDs within cells, we utilized the DCFH-DA and DHE probes. DCFH-DA probe interacts with ROS, resulting in the formation of 2,7-dichlorofluorescein (DCF), and the DHE probe is a commonly used fluorescent probe for detecting ·O2
                        –. In the DCFH-DA experiment, cells treated with rosup displayed a pronounced green fluorescence, signifying that Rosup effectively increased ROS levels. In contrast, pre-incubation with GH-CDs markedly reduced the green fluorescence, demonstrating that GH-CDs are capable of scavenging ROS (Fig. 3

                        A). We further utilized flow cytometry to quantify the scavenging efficiency (Fig. 3
                        B-C). Meanwhile, DHE fluorescence images showed similar results (
                           Figure S5
                        ). Mitochondria are the primary ROS source, and the subcellular co-localization of GH-CDs showed that they co-localized well with mitochondria (
                           Figure S6
                        ), which also indicated GH-CDs had excellent intracellular ROS scavenging potential. On this basis, we further investigated its protective effects against cellular oxidative stress damage. H2O2 was used to induce oxidative damage, and by MTT assay we could observe that cells pretreated with GH-CDs showed significantly higher cell viability (
                           Figure S7
                        ). Furthermore, AM/PI staining of cells exposed to H2O2 revealed a red signal that is characteristic of cell death. In contrast, when cells were pre-treated with GH-CDs, the intensity of the red signal was notably reduced. This reduction suggested that GH-CDs had the potential to mitigate cell death induced by H2O2 (Fig. 3
                        D). These results demonstrated that GH-CDs could be taken up by cells and internalized to mitochondrial sites to scavenge ROS and protect the cells from oxidative damage.
